    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nIf you have typos in your config, it may or may not signal to you about that. For example, if you just open your editor with \"broken\" config, you don't see any error. If you open your `init.lua` and do `:source %`, you get an error from `__newindex` metafunction.\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\nHaving this file and trying to do different things.\r\n```lua\r\nvim.o.numbers = true -- should be vim.o.number\r\n```\r\nFirst how to observe zero errors.\r\n* a) No error. Just having file above as `init.lua` where it belongs.\r\n* b) No error. `nvim -u` option\r\nI tried both `nvim -u init.lua` (one that would be loaded by default),  `nvim -u init.new.lua`, `nvim -u new.init.lua` (just to be sure).\r\n\r\nNow how to observe errors.\r\n* a) Error `nvim init.lua` and then `:source %`. \r\n![image](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/42647349/b10bb15e-f71e-4d57-a626-fec1888bdeb8)\r\n(Sorry for screenshot, I still need to learn how to copy-paste in tmux)\r\n* b) Error. `nvim init.lua --cmd ':source %'`\r\nSame error, but without colours.\r\n* c) Error. Change `vim.o.numbers` to `vim.opt.numbers = true`, and just run `nvim`\r\n![image](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/42647349/79b1ebf7-407c-4c13-b883-b492a3b65fd4)\r\nThis means that `vim.opt` catches an error in both cases.\r\n\r\nFrom (c) I would guess, we might have some weird behaviour in __newindex for `vim.o`.\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nEvery case results in an error from (a).\r\n\r\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\nNVIM v0.9.1 Build type: Release LuaJIT 2.1.1692616192     system vimrc file: \"$VIM/sysinit.vim\"   fall-back for $VIM: \"/usr/share/nvim\"  Run :checkhealth for more info\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nno, vim doesn't have .lua config\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nArchLinux, pacman v6.0.2\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nalacritty + tmux\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\ntmux-256color\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\npacman",
